title: Add query timeout functions and parameters (closes #10)
body:
The patch contains:

- New functions `odbcSetQueryTimeout` and `odbcGetQueryTimeout`
- New parameter `query_timeout` in the functions `sqlPrepare` and `sqlExecute`
- Roxygen documentation
- R testing script for manual testing with MS SQL Server on Windows (in "tests/manual/test_query_timeout_with_MS_SQL.R")
- some minor fixes of documentation errors in the functions `sqlPrepare` and `sqlExecute`

Closes https://github.com/zozlak/RODBCext/issues/10

**Open issues:**

- `errors` parameter is ignored when setting the query timeout via param `query_timeout`: An error is still thrown (not wrapped and replaced by an error return code) that is caused by setting the query timeout value.

repo.description: Personal fork of the read-only repo of the R package RODBCext (ODBC Database Access for R with prepared statements))
repo.name: RODBCext

title: Patch 1 - seq_len
body:
Hi @zozlak, I'm excited about using parameterized queries with R and SQL Server.  Thanks for this package.  

I saw a place in the `sqlExecute.R` code that _would_ be unprotected from a 0-row data frame if it ever was disconnected from the `if(fetch == FALSE | nrow(data) < 1){` block above.  I changed the instances in the Rmd file too.  I know that your CSVs have more than 0 rows, but someone who copies them as examples may not have the protections against it.

Also, I added an Rproj file to make it a little easier for some people to build/check with the proper architecture arguments.

References
- http://stackoverflow.com/questions/24917228/proper-way-to-loop-over-the-length-of-a-dataframe-in-r
- http://r.789695.n4.nabble.com/seq-along-and-rep-along-td4270377.html
